he life of your tires.</p><h2>3. Check your tire pressure</h2><p>Ensuring your tires are inflated to the manufacturer’s recommended PSI helps prevent premature tire wear from too much flexing and overloading. Properly inflated tires also improve handling and fuel economy because it takes less energy to make your tires roll.</p><p>Since changes in temperature can alter your tire’s pressure, it’s important to check your tires’ PSI regularly.</p><p>If you can, get in the habit of checking your tire pressure once a month or even every time you fuel up. To learn how to check and inflate tires yourself, read our article <a href=\"$url('Page-Show', 'cid', 'how-to-check-tire-pressure')$\" target=\"_self\" data-link-type=\"page\" data-link-label=\"Check Tire Pressure\" data-content-page-id=\"how-to-check-tire-pressure\">How to Check Tire Pressure: A 5-step Guide.&nbsp;</a></p><h2>4. Store your tires smarter</h2><p>People love the sun. Tire’s don’t. Exposure to the sun’s harmful UV rays can cause weather cracking, often on the sidewalls and shoulder. If you drive all-weather tires year-round, try to avoid parking in direct sunlight. If you swap out your tires each season, make sure your tires are stored in a place that’s cool and out of sun’s reach.</p><p>Or, you can store your tires with us! Learn more about the benefits and convenience of using&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.kaltire.com/en/tire-storage/\" target=\"_self\" data-link-type=\"external\" data-link-label=\"https://www.kaltire.com/en/tire-storage/\">Kal’s Tire Lodge</a>.</p><h2>5. Don’t weigh your tires down</h2><p>Packing strategically can also help your tires last longer. By keeping heavy items in the trunk or hatch rather than the roof box, you won’t hinder your car’s centre of gravity and you’ll make it easier for your tires to roll, which improves fuel economy as well as tire life.</p>",
